insert into public.questions
  (id, parent_id, type, category, subtopic, importance, difficulty, candidate_level, region, question, key_points, model_answer)
values
(2016, NULL, 'primary', $x$M&A$x$, $x$PIK Financed Accretion$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$An acquirer earns 800M of net income on 400M shares, so 2.00 of EPS, and trades at a 12x P/E (a 24 share price). It buys a target earning 180M for a 2,000M equity purchase price, funded with 1,200M of PIK notes carrying a 9% rate and 800M of stock issued at 24. The tax rate is 25%. Is the deal accretive or dilutive, and by how much? Be careful about how the PIK feature hits earnings.$x$, $x$["Standalone EPS 2.00 at 12x P/E", "PIK Interest Still Hits P&L Despite Being Non-Cash", "1,200M At 9% = 108M Pre-Tax, 81M After-Tax", "800M Stock At 24 = 33.3M New Shares", "Combined NI 899M Over 433.3M Shares", "New EPS ~2.07, ~3.7% Accretive", "Non-Cash Financing Is Not Free To EPS"]$x$::jsonb, $x$I start with the acquirers standalone: 800 of net income on 400 shares is 2.00 of EPS at a 12 times multiple. Now the deal. The PIK notes are the trap most people miss - PIK means the interest accrues onto the principal rather than being paid in cash, but it still hits the income statement as interest expense and is generally tax deductible. So 1,200 of notes at 9 percent is 108 of pre-tax interest, or 81 after tax at a 25 percent rate. The 800 of stock issued at 24 adds 33.3 million new shares. Combined net income is 800 plus the targets 180 minus 81 of after-tax PIK interest, which is 899. Combined shares are 433.3 million. New EPS is about 2.07, so the deal is roughly 3.7 percent accretive. The teaching point is that non-cash financing is not free to EPS - PIK and the coupon on a convertible both drag earnings even though no cash leaves the door, so do not confuse cash flow with accretion.$x$),
(2017, NULL, 'primary', $x$M&A$x$, $x$EPS Accretion Bridge$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$Build me an EPS bridge that decomposes the accretion drivers. An acquirer earns 600M on 200M shares (3.00 EPS) and does an all-cash deal for a 1,500M equity purchase price, funding 500M from balance-sheet cash yielding 4% pre-tax and 1,000M of new debt at 6% pre-tax. The target earns 110M standalone and the tax rate is 25%. Bridge from 3.00 to the combined EPS, line item by line item.$x$, $x$["All-Cash So Share Count Unchanged", "Target Earnings +0.55 Per Share", "Foregone After-Tax Interest On Cash -0.075", "New Debt After-Tax Interest -0.225", "Combined NI 650M, EPS 3.25, +8.3%", "Bridge Isolates Each Driver Per Share", "Earnings Yield Clears After-Tax Funding Cost"]$x$::jsonb, $x$I bridge from the standalone 3.00. The acquirer earns 600 on 200 shares, and because this is an all-cash deal there are no new shares, so the denominator never moves - every effect lands fully on EPS. First driver: the target adds 110 of net income, which is 0.55 per share - the biggest positive. Second: I funded 500 from balance-sheet cash that was yielding 4 percent, so I give up 20 pre-tax, or 15 after tax, which is a drag of about 0.075 per share. Third: 1,000 of new debt at 6 percent is 60 pre-tax, 45 after tax, a drag of roughly 0.225 per share. Netting the three, combined net income is 650 and EPS is 3.25, so the deal is 8.3 percent accretive and the bridge is plus 0.55, minus 0.075, minus 0.225. The point of decomposing it this way is that it shows exactly where accretion comes from - here the targets earnings yield easily clears the after-tax cost of the cash and debt used to buy it.$x$),
(2018, NULL, 'primary', $x$M&A$x$, $x$Contribution And Exchange Ratio$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$Run me a contribution analysis on multiple metrics and recommend an exchange ratio. The acquirer has 6,000M of equity value, 800M of EBITDA and 4,000M of revenue across 200M shares; the target has 1,500M of equity value, 250M of EBITDA and 1,200M of revenue across 100M shares. What does the target contribute, what ownership and exchange ratio fall out at market, and where would you land once you factor in a premium?$x$, $x$["Target Contributes 20% Equity, ~24% EBITDA, 23% Revenue", "At-Market Ownership Tracks Equity Value = 20%", "At-Market Exchange Ratio 15/30 = 0.50", "Tension: Operating Contribution Exceeds Ownership", "~0.625 Ratio Matches EBITDA Contribution", "20% Premium Lifts Ratio To 0.60, Ownership ~23%", "Anchor Recommendation To Blended Zone"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Contribution analysis asks what each side brings versus what it gets. The acquirer has 6,000 of equity value, 800 of EBITDA and 4,000 of revenue; the target has 1,500, 250 and 1,200. So the target contributes 20 percent of equity value, about 24 percent of EBITDA and 23 percent of revenue. In a no-premium all-stock merger, ownership tracks relative equity value, so the target gets 20 percent. With the acquirer at 30 a share and the target at 15, the at-market exchange ratio is 15 over 30, or 0.50. The tension is obvious - the target contributes more of the EBITDA and revenue than the 20 percent ownership it would receive, so its board will argue for a premium. To give it ownership equal to its EBITDA contribution I would need a ratio near 0.625. A 20 percent premium lifts the ratio to 0.60 and ownership to about 23 percent, which roughly aligns ownership with operating contribution. I would anchor my recommendation around that blended zone.$x$),
(2019, NULL, 'primary', $x$M&A$x$, $x$Sources And Uses Refinancing$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$A strategic buyer is acquiring a target and wants to refinance the targets existing debt at close. Build the sources and uses. Uses are a 2,500M equity purchase price, 600M to repay the targets existing debt, and 90M of transaction fees. On the sources side the buyer contributes 400M of balance-sheet cash and raises 1,800M of new debt, with stock as the plug. Walk me through it and tell me the implied enterprise value.$x$, $x$["Uses: 2,500M Equity + 600M Debt Refi + 90M Fees = 3,190M", "Fees Are A Real Use That Must Be Funded", "Refinancing Target Debt Is A Use Of Cash", "Sources: 400M Cash + 1,800M Debt + Plug", "Stock Plug Of 990M Balances To 3,190M", "Implied EV = 2,500M Equity + 600M Debt = 3,100M", "New Financing Covers Both Equity And Debt Payoff"]$x$::jsonb, $x$A sources and uses just makes the funding balance. On the uses side I have the equity purchase price to target shareholders of 2,500, repayment of the targets existing debt of 600 because the buyer wants a clean capital structure and the debt likely has change-of-control language, and transaction fees of about 90 for advisory, financing and legal. That totals 3,190 of uses. Note the implied enterprise value here is 3,100 - the 2,500 of equity plus the 600 of debt being taken out. On the sources side, the buyer puts in 400 of balance-sheet cash, raises 1,800 of new debt, and the plug is 990 of acquirer stock issued to the seller. Sources tie to 3,190. The two things interviewers want to hear: fees are a real use that has to be funded, and refinancing target debt is itself a use of cash, so the new financing has to cover both the equity check and that payoff, not just the headline price.$x$),
(2020, NULL, 'primary', $x$M&A$x$, $x$Fixed-Value Collar Boundary$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$A stock deal promises the target 50 of value per share, with a fixed-value collar around a 40 reference price and boundaries at 36 and 44. Show me the exchange-ratio math at the collar boundaries, what the target actually receives if the acquirers stock falls to 30, and who bears the risk on each side of the band.$x$, $x$["Inside Band Value Fixed At 50, Ratio Floats As 50/Price", "Ratio Freezes At Boundaries", "Floor 36: Ratio Locks At 1.3889 (Max Shares)", "Cap 44: Ratio Locks At 1.1364 (Min Shares)", "Below 36 Value Floats Down: At 30 Only ~41.67", "Target Bears Tail Downside, Captures Upside Above Cap", "Acquirer Caps Dilution"]$x$::jsonb, $x$A fixed-value collar guarantees the target a set dollar value - here 50 per share - but only within a band of acquirer prices, say 36 to 44, with a 40 reference. Inside the band the value is fixed at 50, so the exchange ratio floats as 50 divided by the price. The collar bites at the boundaries because the ratio freezes there. At the 36 floor the ratio locks at 50 over 36, about 1.3889 shares, the maximum the acquirer will issue. At the 44 cap it locks at 50 over 44, about 1.1364 shares, the minimum. Below 36 the ratio stays fixed, so value now floats down - at a 30 stock the target receives 1.3889 times 30, only about 41.67 of value, not 50. So the target is protected against modest weakness but bears the tail risk of a real collapse, while the acquirer caps its dilution. Above 44 the mirror holds: the ratio is floored, so the target captures upside beyond 50. The collar trades certainty for protection against extreme moves on both sides.$x$),
(2021, NULL, 'primary', $x$M&A$x$, $x$Pro-Forma Balance Sheet$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$Walk me through goodwill and the day-one pro-forma balance sheet. The buyer pays 1,000M for a target with 400M of book equity, funding 300M from balance-sheet cash and 700M of new debt. Purchase accounting steps PP&E up by 120M and books 180M of newly identified intangibles, with deferred taxes at 25%. Give me the goodwill and how the consolidated balance sheet ties out.$x$, $x$["Total Step-Up 300M Creates 75M DTL At 25%", "FV Net Identifiable Assets = 400 + 300 - 75 = 625M", "Goodwill = 1,000 - 625 = 375M", "Assets: Target Tangibles + 120 Step-Up + 180 Intangibles + 375 Goodwill", "Liabilities: Assume Target Debt + 700 New Debt + 75 DTL", "Target Old Equity Eliminated, Buyer Equity Unchanged (All-Cash)", "Assets And Claims Both Tie Out"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Goodwill is the plug between price and the fair value of what you acquire. The target has 400 of book equity. I step PP&E up by 120 and book 180 of newly identified intangibles, a total step-up of 300. That step-up creates a deferred tax liability at 25 percent, so 75, because the write-up raises book basis without raising tax basis. Fair value of net identifiable assets is therefore 400 plus 300 minus 75, or 625. Against a 1,000 purchase price, goodwill is 375. For the day-one balance sheet I consolidate at fair value: target cash and tangible assets come on, PP&E carries the 120 step-up, I add 180 of intangibles and 375 of goodwill on the asset side; on the other side I assume the targets liabilities, add the new 700 of acquisition debt, and add the 75 DTL. The buyer funds 300 from its own cash and 700 of new debt, the targets old equity is eliminated, and the acquirers equity is unchanged because it is an all-cash deal. Assets and claims both tie out.$x$),
(2022, NULL, 'primary', $x$M&A$x$, $x$Synergies Versus Premium$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$Quantify net synergies against the premium paid and tell me how much value is created versus transferred. The target trades unaffected at 2,000M and the acquirer pays a 30% premium. Run-rate after-tax synergies are 100M a year, the discount rate is 8%, and one-time integration cost is 200M after tax. How much value does the acquirer actually keep, and how does the picture change if synergies disappoint?$x$, $x$["Premium = 600M, Transferred Straight To Target Holders", "Gross PV Synergies = 100/0.08 = 1,250M", "Net Of 200M Integration = ~1,050M Created", "Value Kept By Acquirer = 1,050 - 600 = ~450M", "~57% Of Net Synergies Handed To Seller", "Deal Still Creates Value But Cushion Is Thin", "At 70M After-Tax Synergies Cushion Nearly Vanishes (Winners Curse)"]$x$::jsonb, $x$This separates value created from value transferred. The target trades unaffected at 2,000. The acquirer pays a 30 percent premium, so 2,600, and that 600 of premium is value handed straight to target shareholders - it is transferred, not created. Now the synergies. Say run-rate after-tax synergies are 100 a year; at an 8 percent discount rate the gross present value is 100 over 0.08, or 1,250. But synergies are not free - netting 200 of one-time integration cost leaves about 1,050 of net synergy value created by the combination. Value created for the acquirers own shareholders is the net synergy value minus the premium paid, so 1,050 minus 600, about 450 of value retained. Put differently, the acquirer is handing roughly 57 percent of the net synergies to the seller through the premium. The deal still creates value, but if synergies came in at 70 after tax instead, net PV drops to around 675 and the acquirers cushion over the premium nearly disappears - that is the winners-curse warning.$x$),
(2023, NULL, 'primary', $x$M&A$x$, $x$Top-Up Option$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'analyst', 'US', $x$A sponsor is acquiring a public company through a two-step tender offer and wants to be able to close the back-end merger fast. Walk me through what a top-up option is, how it interacts with the squeeze-out threshold, and whether it still matters given DGCL 251(h).$x$, $x$["Top-up option lets acquirer buy newly issued shares at offer price", "Purpose: cross the 90% short-form merger (section 253) threshold", "Avoids a second shareholder vote and proxy", "Limited by authorized-but-unissued share capacity", "251(h) removes the need if the requisite shares (majority) tendered", "Top-up largely vestigial for 251(h)-eligible friendly deals", "Still relevant where 251(h) unavailable or authorized shares insufficient"]$x$::jsonb, $x$A top-up option is a contractual right the target gives the buyer to purchase newly issued primary shares, at the tender-offer price, right after the offer closes. The point is mechanical: under older Delaware practice an acquirer holding 90 percent of each class could do a short-form merger under section 253 with no vote and no proxy, fast and certain. If the tender got you to, say, 82 percent, the top-up lets you issue enough fresh shares to vault over 90, avoiding a long-form merger and a back-end shareholder meeting. The binding constraint is authorized-but-unissued shares: if the charter lacks headroom the option caps out and cannot get you there, which is why diligence on authorized shares matters. Now, under section 251(h), if you tender for and acquire the shares needed to approve the merger, generally a majority of the outstanding, you complete the second-step merger immediately without ever crossing 90 percent. So for a 251(h)-eligible friendly deal the top-up is largely vestigial. I would still keep it where 251(h) is unavailable: certain non-251(h) structures, multiple share classes, or interested-party complications.$x$),
(2024, NULL, 'primary', $x$M&A$x$, $x$Section 363 Sale$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'US', $x$You are advising a strategic buyer that wants to acquire a distressed competitor out of Chapter 11 through a section 363 sale. Walk me through why a buyer likes a 363 process, what the stalking-horse and bid-protection dynamics are, and the main risks you flag.$x$, $x$["Free and clear of liens and claims under 363(f)", "Court-approved auction with a stalking-horse floor", "Stalking horse gets break fee and expense reimbursement", "Bid protections and overbid increments are court-scrutinized", "Successor-liability cutoff is strong but not absolute", "Speed; cherry-pick assets and reject contracts under 365", "Risk of being topped at auction; no deal certainty"]$x$::jsonb, $x$The big draw of a 363 sale is that the buyer takes the assets free and clear of liens, claims and most successor liability under section 363(f), with a court order blessing it, which is far cleaner than buying a troubled company outside bankruptcy. The way I run it: my client signs an asset purchase agreement as the stalking horse, which sets the floor price and deal terms, and in exchange we negotiate bid protections, typically a break fee around 2 to 3 percent of value plus expense reimbursement, and minimum overbid increments. Those protections compensate us for setting the market, but the court and creditors scrutinize them so they cannot be so rich they chill bidding. We also cherry-pick: assume the contracts and leases we want and have the debtor reject the rest under section 365. The risks are real. We can be topped at the auction, so there is no deal certainty even after months of work. Free-and-clear is strong but not absolute, so I diligence successor-liability exposure on things like environmental and certain tort or labor claims. And the timeline, while fast, runs on the court's calendar, not ours.$x$),
(2025, NULL, 'primary', $x$M&A$x$, $x$Bear-Hug Letter$x$, 'standard', 3, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$Your client receives an unsolicited bear-hug letter: a public, premium all-cash proposal sent straight to the board. Explain what a bear hug is, why the bidder chose this tactic, and how you advise the board to respond.$x$, $x$["Public premium unsolicited proposal to pressure the board", "Weaponizes fiduciary duty and shareholder expectations", "Board not obligated to sell but must consider in good faith", "Avoid reflexive rejection; document the process", "Confirm advisors and form a special committee if conflicts exist", "Buy time to assess standalone value and alternatives", "Response ranges from reasoned rejection to engaging under an NDA"]$x$::jsonb, $x$A bear hug is an unsolicited acquisition proposal, usually at an eye-catching premium, that the bidder makes public or sends directly to the board precisely to put the directors on the spot. The tactic weaponizes fiduciary duty: by going over management's head and waving a rich price at shareholders, the bidder makes a flat no look like the board is ignoring value. My first message is do not panic and do not reflexively reject, but understand you are not obligated to sell. What you are obligated to do is consider a credible offer in good faith and run a clean, well-documented process, because how this looks later matters. Practically, I have the board confirm advisors, consider a special committee if there are conflicts, and buy time to assess the standalone plan and whether the price actually beats it. We test the credibility and financing of the bid and keep public statements disciplined. The response then spans a spectrum: a reasoned rejection if the standalone case is stronger, engagement under an NDA, or using the bid to canvass other buyers. The worst outcome is a defensive crouch the bidder exploits against you.$x$),
(2026, NULL, 'primary', $x$M&A$x$, $x$Stranded Costs$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$A parent is carving out a division that currently relies on shared corporate functions. The carve-out reports 400M of EBITDA, the TSA charges the buyer 30M a year for shared services for 18 months, but on a standalone basis the business will need 45M of run-rate cost to replace them, and the parent is left with 25M of stranded cost. Walk me through the standalone EBITDA the buyer should underwrite and the stranded-cost issue for the seller.$x$, $x$["Carve-out financials carry allocations, not true standalone cost", "TSA pricing is temporary and usually below real standalone cost", "Incremental dis-synergy is the 15M gap (TSA 30M vs standalone 45M)", "Adjusted standalone EBITDA ~385M, not the 400M headline", "Model the TSA cliff plus one-time stand-up / separation capex", "Size the purchase multiple off the normalized number", "Seller's 25M stranded cost must be eliminated or RemainCo margin falls"]$x$::jsonb, $x$The trap is taking the 400M of carve-out EBITDA at face value, because those financials carry parent cost allocations, not the true cost of running this business alone. The TSA charges 30M for 18 months, but that is a temporary bridge priced near the parent's marginal cost, not what the buyer pays once it stands the functions up itself, which here is 45M of run-rate cost. So the real standalone overhead is about 15M higher than what the carve-out and the TSA imply, and adjusted standalone EBITDA is closer to 385M, not the 400M headline. That 15M dis-synergy between the 30M TSA and the 45M standalone cost hits the buyer the day the TSA rolls off, so I model that cliff plus the one-time stand-up capex to build out IT, HR and finance, and I size the purchase multiple off the normalized number. On the other side, the seller carries 25M of stranded cost: overhead that used to be spread across the division and now sits on RemainCo with no revenue behind it. If the parent cannot eliminate or re-absorb it, RemainCo margins fall, so a credible plan to take those costs out is part of the deal story for both sides.$x$),
(2027, NULL, 'primary', $x$M&A$x$, $x$Going-Private Fairness$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'US', $x$A controlling shareholder who already owns 60 percent wants to squeeze out the public minority and take the company private. Walk me through the fairness and litigation dynamics, and what structure gets the buyer the most deferential standard of review in Delaware.$x$, $x$["Controller conflict triggers entire-fairness default", "Both fair price and fair dealing are tested", "MFW framework shifts review to business judgment", "Conditioned upfront on special committee AND majority-of-minority", "Independent, empowered committee with its own advisors", "Minority vote must be fully informed and uncoerced", "Residual appraisal and disclosure-litigation exposure"]$x$::jsonb, $x$When a controller stands on both sides of a squeeze-out, Delaware's default is entire fairness, the most demanding standard, and the controller bears the burden of proving both a fair price and a fair process, what courts call fair dealing. That is a hard place to litigate from. The fix is the MFW framework. If, from the outset and before any economic negotiation, the controller conditions the deal on two protections, approval by a well-functioning independent special committee that can say no and hire its own bankers and counsel, and a non-waivable majority-of-the-minority vote by fully informed, uncoerced shareholders, then review drops to business judgment, highly deferential and usually ending the case early. The key word is upfront: bolt these on late and you lose the cleansing effect. So my advice is commit to both conditions in the first proposal letter, let the committee actually negotiate price at arm's length, and make the disclosure airtight. Even then I flag residual exposure: appraisal, where dissenters ask the court for fair value, and disclosure-based litigation, which is why the proxy must be complete and accurate.$x$),
(2028, NULL, 'primary', $x$M&A$x$, $x$Toehold Strategy$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'analyst', 'US', $x$A strategic acquirer is considering quietly building a stake in a target before making an approach. Walk me through the toehold and creeping-control strategy, the economic logic, and the disclosure and regulatory tripwires that constrain it.$x$, $x$["Toehold lowers blended cost and funds the loss if outbid", "Schedule 13D triggers at 5%, now within five business days", "Intent disclosure tips the market and spikes the price", "HSR pre-acquisition notification threshold and waiting period", "Poison pill trigger (~10-15%) caps accumulation", "State control-share and business-combination statutes bite", "Creeping control via open market eventually forces a formal bid"]$x$::jsonb, $x$A toehold is a stake the bidder accumulates before going public with an approach. The logic is twofold: it lowers your blended cost basis, and if you get outbid you still own shares that have risen, so you profit on the rival's deal rather than just eating costs. But you cannot quietly accumulate forever. The first tripwire is Schedule 13D: once you cross 5 percent with control intent you must file within a short window, now five business days under the amended rules, and that filing discloses your stake and purpose, which tips the market and spikes the price, raising the cost of everything you buy after. So the toehold benefit is capped by disclosure. Second, antitrust: HSR requires pre-acquisition notification and a waiting period once you cross the size thresholds. Third, target defenses bite: a poison pill typically triggers around 10 to 15 percent, capping accumulation, and state control-share and business-combination statutes restrict voting and back-end mergers for a large unblessed holder. So creeping control through open-market buying is real but bounded; past a point you must convert the toehold into a formal bid.$x$),
(2029, NULL, 'primary', $x$M&A$x$, $x$Consortium Bid$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$Two private equity sponsors want to form a consortium to bid on a large public target. Set aside governance between the sponsors and focus on the antitrust and financing wrinkles a club deal raises today. Walk me through them.$x$, $x$["Club-deal bid coordination raises bid-rigging / collusion scrutiny", "Clean teams; no information sharing with rival bidders", "Combined portfolio holdings aggregate for HSR analysis", "Bigger equity cheque reduces single-sponsor concentration", "Private credit / unitranche fills a tougher leveraged-loan market", "Pin down financing certainty and reverse-termination-fee allocation", "Allocate antitrust risk; avoid loose joint-and-several exposure"]$x$::jsonb, $x$On antitrust, the first issue is the club itself. Sponsors teaming up is legal, but coordinating bids has a history of scrutiny: the concern is clubbing suppresses competition and lowers the price the target gets, which looks like bid-rigging if would-be rivals collude. So I keep the consortium clean: partners share information only within the bidding group and never with competing bidders. The second wrinkle is portfolio overlap: both sponsors own other companies, and the agencies aggregate the combined holdings, so a market the target competes in may overlap with a portfolio company of either, driving HSR analysis and even a second request. On financing, the point of the club is a bigger equity cheque, reducing single-fund concentration and reaching a deal too large to underwrite alone. In today's tougher leveraged-loan market much of that debt comes from private credit, unitranche from direct lenders, trading cost for speed. With two sponsors I also pin down certainty up front: who funds what equity, how the debt commitment is split, and how the reverse termination fee and antitrust risk are allocated.$x$) on conflict do nothing;
